  "original_title": "\u0dad\u0dc0\u0dad\u0dca 188\u0d9a\u0dca \u0d85\u0daf \u0d9a\u0ddc\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0da7 \u0dba\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Another 188 are leaving for Korea today",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "188 Sri Lankans contracted for Korean jobs are scheduled to leave for South Korea tonight (2022.06.28). This is the 721st group to leave for South Korea.",
        "Manusha Nanayakkara, Minister of Labor and Foreign Employment, in a recent discussion with Lee Chu Chul, Resident Representative of the Department of Human Resources in Korea, focused on sending 5800 Sri Lankans to Korea for employment in six months. As a result, employment agreements are being signed soon and Sri Lankans are being deported to South Korea.",
        "South Korea is recruiting people for Korean jobs in accordance with the diplomatic agreement signed between Sri Lanka and South Korea, and the Sri Lanka Bureau of Foreign Employment is expediting the recruitment process after receiving the relevant agreements. Despite some delays in recruitment and recruitment for foreign employment during the Kovid epidemic, the Bureau's continued work with the Korean government has led to an increase in the recruitment of workers for Korean jobs."
      ],
